\b\fs34 \cf0 2.4\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 DO
\f0\b  Loops\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Although the annual repayments on a home loan are usually fixed, the outstanding balance does not decline linearly with time. The next program demonstrates this with the aid of a 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loop.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       PROGRAM REDUCE \
      WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT=*)'Enter amount, % rate, years' \
      READ(UNIT=*, FMT=*) AMOUNT, PCRATE, NYEARS \
      RATE = PCRATE / 100.0 \
      REPAY = RATE * AMOUNT / (1.0 - (1.0+RATE)**(-NYEARS)) \
      WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT=*)'Annual repayments are ', REPAY \
      WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT=*)'End of Year  Balance' \
      DO 15,IYEAR = 1,NYEARS \
          AMOUNT = AMOUNT + (AMOUNT * RATE) - REPAY \
          WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT=*) IYEAR, AMOUNT  \
15    CONTINUE \
      END \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The first part of the program is similar to the earlier one. It continues with another 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement which produces headings for the two columns of output which will be produced later on.\
The 
\f1 DO
\f0  statement then defines the start of a loop: the statements in the loop are executed repeatedly with the loop-control variable 
\f1 IYEAR
\f0  taking successive values from 1 to 
\f1 NYEARS
\f0 . The first statement in the loop updates the value of 
\f1 AMOUNT
\f0  by adding the annual interest to it and subtracting the actual repayment. This results in 
\f1 AMOUNT
\f0  storing the amount of the loan still owing at the end of the year. The next statement outputs the year number and the latest value of 
\f1 AMOUNT
\f0 . After this there is a 
\f1 CONTINUE
\f0  statement which actually does nothing but act as a place-marker. The loop ends at the 
\f1 CONTINUE
\f0  statement because it is attached to the label, 
\f1 15
\f0 , that was specified in the 
\f1 DO
\f0  statement at the start of the loop.\
The active statements in the loop have been indented a little to the right of those outside it: this is not required but is very common practice among Fortran programmers because it makes the structure of the program more conspicuous.\
The program REDUCE produces a table of values which, while mathematically correct, is not very easy to read:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 Enter amount, % rate, years \
2000, 9.5, 5 \
Annual repayments are    520.8728     \
End of Year  Balance \
      1   1669.127     \
      2   1306.822     \
      3   910.0968     \
      4   475.6832     \
      5  2.9800416E-04 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 2.5\'a0\'a0Formatted Output\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The table of values would have a better appearance if the decimal points were properly aligned and if there were only two digits after them. The last figure in the table is actually less than a thirtieth of a penny, which is effectively zero to within the accuracy of the machine. A better layout can be produced easily enough by using an explicit format specification instead of the list-directed output used up to now. To do this, the last 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement in the program should be replaced with one like this:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT='(1X,I9,F11.2)') IYEAR, AMOUNT
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 The amended program will then produce a neater tabulation:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 Enter amount, % rate, years \
2000, 9.5, 5 \
Annual repayments are    520.8728     \
End of Year  Balance \
        1    1669.13 \
        2    1306.82 \
        3     910.10 \
        4     475.68 \
        5        .00 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The format specification has to be enclosed in parentheses and, as it is actually a character constant, in a pair of apostrophes as well. The first item in the format list, 
\f1 1X
\f0 , is needed to cope with the carriage-control convention: it provides an additional blank at the start of each line which is later removed by the Fortran system. There is no logical explanation for this: it is there for compatibility with very early Fortran system. The remaining items specify the layout of each number: 
\f1 I9
\f0  specifies that the first number, an integer, should be occupy a field 9 columns wide; similarly 
\f1 F11.2
\f0  puts the second number, a real (floating-point) value, into a field 11 characters wide with exactly 2 digits after the decimal point. Numbers are always right-justified in each field. The field widths in this example have been chosen so that the columns of figures line up satisfactorily with the headings.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 2.6\'a0\'a0Functions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Fortran provides a useful selection of intrinsic functions to carry out various mathematical operations such as square root, maximum and minimum, sine, cosine, etc., as well as various data type conversions. You can also write your own functions. The next example, which computes the area of a triangle, shows both forms of function in action.\
The formulae for the area of a triangle with sides of length a, b, and c is: \

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trwWidth23420\trftsWidth3 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth23300\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640

\itap2\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1660\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap2\pardeftab720\qc
\cf0 s = (a + b + c)/2\nestcell \lastrow\nestrow\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trwWidth23420\trftsWidth3 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth23300\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640

\itap2\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth3280\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap2\pardeftab720\qc
\cf0 area = sqrt(s.(s
\f2 -
\f0 a).(s
\f2 -
\f0 b).(s
\f2 -
\f0 c))\nestcell \lastrow\nestrow\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       PROGRAM TRIANG \
      WRITE(UNIT=*,FMT=*)'Enter lengths of three sides:' \
      READ(UNIT=*,FMT=*) SIDEA, SIDEB, SIDEC \
      WRITE(UNIT=*,FMT=*)'Area is ', AREA3(SIDEA,SIDEB,SIDEC) \
      END \
\
      FUNCTION AREA3(A, B, C) \
*Computes the area of a triangle from lengths of sides \
      S = (A + B + C)/2.0 \
      AREA3 = SQRT(S * (S-A) * (S-B) * (S-C)) \
      END \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This program consists of two program units. The first is the main program, and it has as similar form to those seen earlier. The only novel feature is that the list of items output by the 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement includes a call to a function called 
\f1 AREA3
\f0 . This computes the area of the triangle. It is an external function which is specified by means of a separate program unit technically known as a function subprogram.\
The external function starts with a 
\f1 FUNCTION
\f0  statement which names the function and specifies its set of dummy arguments. This function has three dummy arguments called 
\f1 A, B,
\f0  and 
\f1 C
\f0 . The values of the actual arguments, 
\f1 SIDEA, SIDEB,
\f0  and 
\f1 SIDEC
\f0 , are transferred to the corresponding dummy arguments when the function is called. Variable names used in the external function have no connection with those of the main program: the actual and dummy argument values are connected only by their relative position in each list. Thus 
\f1 SIDEA
\f0  transfers its value to 
\f1 A
\f0 , and so on. The name of the function can be used as a variable within the subprogram unit; this variable must be assigned a value before the function returns control, as this is the value returned to the calling program.\
Within the function the dummy arguments can also be used as variables. The first assignment statement computes the sum, divides it by two, and assigns it to a local variable, 
\f1 S
\f0 ; the second assignment statement uses the intrinsic function 
\f1 SQRT
\f0  which computes the square-root of its argument. The result is returned to the calling program by assigning it to the variable which has the same name as the function.\
The 
\f1 END
\f0  statement in a procedure does not cause the program to stop but just returns control to the calling program unit.\
There is one other novelty: a comment line describing the action of the function. Any line of text can be inserted as a comment anywhere except after an 
\f1 END
\f0  statement. Comment lines have an asterisk in the first column.\
These two program units could be held on separate source files and even compiled separately. An additional stage, usually called linking, is needed to construct the complete executable program out of these separately compiled object modules. This seems an unnecessary overhead for such simple programs but, as described in the next section, it has advantages when building large programs.\
In this very simple example it was not really necessary to separate the calculation from the input/output operations but in more complicated cases this is usually a sensible practice. For one thing it allows the same calculation to be executed anywhere else that it is required. For another, it reduces the complexity of the program by dividing the work up into small independent units which are easier to manage.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 2.7\'a0\'a0IF-blocks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Another important control structure in Fortran is the 
\f1 IF
\f0  statement which allows a block of statements to be executed conditionally, or allows a choice to be made between different courses of action.\
One obvious defect of the function 
\f1 AREA3
\f0  is that has no protection against incorrect input. Many sets of three real numbers could not possibly form the sides of a triangle, for example 1.0, 2.0, and 7.0. A little analysis shows that in all such impossible cases the argument of the square root function will be negative, which is illegal. Fortran systems should detect errors like this at run-time but will vary in their response. Even so, a message like ``negative argument for square-root'' may not be enough to suggest to the user what is wrong. The next version of the function is slightly more user-friendly; unfortunately because one cannot use a WRITE statement inside a function which is itself being used in a WRITE statement, the error message has to come from a STOP statement.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       REAL FUNCTION AREA3(A, B, C) \
*Computes the area of a triangle from lengths of its sides. \
*If arguments are invalid issues error message and returns zero. \
      REAL A, B, C \
      S = (A + B + C)/2.0 \
      FACTOR = S * (S-A) * (S-B) * (S-C) \
      IF(FACTOR .LE. 0.0) THEN \
          STOP 'Impossible triangle'\
      ELSE \
          AREA3 = SQRT(FACTOR) \
      END IF \
      END \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The 
\f1 IF
\f0  statement works with the 
\f1 ELSE
\f0  and 
\f1 END IF
\f0  statements to enclose two blocks of code. The statements in the first block are only executed if the expression in the 
\f1 IF
\f0  statement is true, those in the second block only if it is false. The statements in each block are indented for visibility, but this is, again, just a sensible programming practice.\
With this modification, the value of 
\f1 FACTOR
\f0  is tested and if it is negative or zero then an error message is produced; 
\f1 AREA
\f0 3 is also set to an impossible value (zero) to flag the mistake. Note that the form ``
\f1 .LE.
\f0 '' is used because the less-than-or-equals character, ``
\f1 <
\f0 '', is not present in the Fortran character set. If 
\f1 FACTOR
\f0  is positive the calculation proceeds as before.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 2.8\'a0\'a0Arrays\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

