\f0  statement, for example, may transfer control to another part of the same program unit, whereas a 
\f1 CALL
\f0  statement or function reference will transfer control temporarily to a procedure.\
A program continues executing until it reaches a 
\f1 STOP
\f0  statement in any program unit, or the 
\f1 END
\f0  statement of the main program unit, or until a fatal error occurs. When a program terminates normally (at 
\f1 STOP
\f0  or 
\f1 END
\f0 ) the Fortran system closes any files still open before returning control to the operating system. But when a program is terminated prematurely files, especially output files, may be left with incomplete or corrupted records.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 4.5\'a0\'a0Symbolic Names\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Symbolic names can be given to items such as variables, arrays, constants, functions, subroutines, and common blocks. All symbolic names must conform to the following simple rule: the first character of each name must be a letter, this may be followed by up to five more letters or digits. Here are some examples of valid symbolic names:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0           I  MATRIX  VOLTS  PIBY4  OLDCHI  TWOX  R2D2  OUTPUT \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

