\f1 \cf0 * = MAX(IRD,IRD,...)
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 returns the largest of its arguments.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 These two functions can, of course, be combined to limit a value to a certain range. For example, to limit a value TEMPER to the range 32 to 212 you can use an expression such as:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 MAX(32.0, MIN(TEMPER, 212.0))
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 Note that the minimum of the range is an argument of the MAX function and vice-versa.\
To find the largest (or smallest) element of a large array it is necessary use a loop.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 *Find largest value in array T of N elements:  \
      TOP = T(1) \
      DO 25,I = 2,N \
         TOP = MAX(T(I), TOP) \
25    CONTINUE \
*TOP now contains the largest element of T. \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

