\f1 \cf0 INDEX
\f0\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0 \cf0 INDEX
\f0  is a search function; it takes two character arguments and returns an integer result. 
\f1 INDEX(S1, S2)
\f0  searches for the character-string 
\f1 S2
\f0  in another string 
\f1 S1
\f0 , which is usually longer. If 
\f1 S2
\f0  is present in 
\f1 S1
\f0  the function returns the character position at which it starts. If there is no match (or 
\f1 S1
\f0  is shorter than 
\f1 S2
\f0 ) then it returns the value zero. For example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       CHARACTER*20 SPELL \
      SPELL  = 'ABRACADABRA' \
      K      = INDEX(SPELL, 'RA') \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Here 
\f1 K will
\f0  be set to 3 because this is the position of the first occurrence of the string 
\f1 'RA'
\f0 . To find the second occurrence it is necessary to restart the search at the next character in the main string, for example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 L = INDEX(SPELL(K+1:), 'RA')
\f0 \
This will return the value 7 because the first occurrence of 
\f1 'RA'
\f0  in the substring 
\f1 'ACADABRA'
\f0  is at position 7. To find its position in the parent string the offset, 
\f1 K
\f0 , must be added, making 10.\
The 
\f1 INDEX
\f0  function is often useful when manipulating character information. Suppose, for example, we have a string NAME containing the a person's surname and initials, e.g.
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 Mozart,W.A 
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 The name can be reformatted to put the initials before the surname and omit the comma like this:\

\f1       CHARACTER NAME*25, PERSON*25 \
*... \
      KCOMMA = INDEX(NAME, ',') \
      KSPACE = INDEX(NAME, ' ') \
      PERSON = NAME(KCOMMA+1:KSPACE-1) // NAME(1:KCOMMA-1) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Then PERSON will contain the string 
\f1 'W.A.Mozart'
\f0  (with blanks appended to the length of 25). Note that a separate variable, 
\f1 PERSON,
\f0  was necessary because of the rule about overlapping strings in assignments.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 LEN
\f0\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The 
\f1 LEN
\f0  function takes a character argument and returns its length as an integer. The argument may be a local character variable or array element but this will just return a constant. 
\f1 LEN
\f0  is more useful in procedures where character dummy arguments (and character function names) may have their length passed over from the calling unit, so that the length may be different on each procedure call. The length returned by 
\f1 LEN
\f0  is that declared for the item. Sometimes it is more useful to find the length excluding trailing blanks. The next function does just that, using 
\f1 LEN
\f0  in the process.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       INTEGER FUNCTION LENGTH(STRING) \
*Returns length of string ignoring trailing blanks \
      CHARACTER*(*) STRING \
      DO 15, I = LEN(STRING), 1, -1 \
         IF(STRING(I:I) .NE. ' ') GO TO 20 \
15    CONTINUE \
20    LENGTH = I \
      END \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 7.6\'a0\'a0Relational Expressions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 A relational expression compares the values of two arithmetic expressions or two character expressions: the result is a logical value, either true or false. Relational expressions are commonly used in 
\f1 IF
\f0  statements, as in this example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       IF(SENSOR .GT. UPPER) THEN \
          CALL COOL \
      ELSE IF(SENSOR .LT. LOWER) THEN \
          CALL HEAT \
      END IF \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The relational operators have forms such as 
\f1 .GT.
\f0  and 
\f1 .LT.
\f0  because the Fortran character set does not include the usual characters 
\f1 .
\f0  and 
\f1 <
\f0 . Relational expressions are most commonly used in 
\f1 IF
\f0  statements, but any logical variable or array element may be used to store a logical value for use later on.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       CHARACTER*10 OPTION \
      LOGICAL EXIT \
      EXIT = OPTION .EQ. 'FINISH'  \
*... \
      IF(EXIT) STOP 'Finish requested' \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Logical expressions are covered in more detail in the next section.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

