\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 less than.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 They take two character arguments (of any length) and return a logical value. Thus the expression:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 LGT('A1', 'AONE')
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 will always have the value false.\
Character comparisons are case-sensitive on machines which have lower-case letters in their character set. It is advisable to convert both arguments to the same case beforehand.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Guidelines\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 Systems which supports both upper and lower-case characters are usually case-sensitive: before testing for the presence of particular keywords or commands it is usually best to convert the input string to a standard case, usually upper-case. Unfortunately there are no standard intrinsic functions to do this, though many systems provide them as an extension.\
In character sorting operations where the strings contain mixtures of letters, digits, or other symbols, you should use the intrinsic functions to make the program portable. In other character comparisons, however, the relational operator notation is probably preferable because it has a more familiar form and may be slightly more efficient.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 7.7\'a0\'a0Logical Expressions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Logical expressions can be used in logical assignment statements, but are most commonly encountered in 
\f1 IF
\f0  statements where there is a compound condition, for example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        IF(AGE .GE. 60 .OR. (STATUS .EQ. 'WIDOW' .AND. \
     $   NCHILD .GT. 0) THEN \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This combines the values of three relational expressions, two of them comparing arithmetic values, the other character values. The logical operators such as 
\f1 .AND.
\f0  and 
\f1 .OR.
\f0  also need decimal points at either end to distinguish them from symbolic names. The 
\f1 .OR.
\f0  operator performs an inclusive or, the exclusive or operator is called 
\f1 .NEQV.
\f0 .\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Rules\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 A logical expression can have any of the following forms:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls13\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls13\ilvl0
\i \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}logical-term
\i0 \
{\listtext	\'95	}\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls13\ilvl0
\f1 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}.NOT.
\f0  
\i logical-term
\i0 \
{\listtext	\'95	}\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls13\ilvl0
\i \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}logical-expression
\i0  \'a0\'a0
\i logical-operator
\i0  \'a0\'a0
\i  logical-term
\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Where: 
\i logical-term
\i0  can be any of the following:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls14\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}logical constant (literal or named),\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}logical variable,\
