\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth3760\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\qc

\f1 \cf0 1
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Advance to top of next page\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1080\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth3760\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\qc

\f1 \cf0 +
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 No advance, i.e.\'a0print on same line\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 An empty record is treated as if it started with a single blank. For example, these statements start a new page with a page number at the top and a title on the third line:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       WRITE(LP, 55) NUMBER, 'Report and Accounts' \
55    FORMAT('1PAGE', I4, /, '0', A) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This carriage-control convention is an absurd relic which causes a multitude of problems in practice. Firstly, systems differ on what they call a ``printer'': it may or may not apply to visual display terminals or to text initially saved on a disc file and later printed out. Some operating systems have a special file type for Fortran formatted output which is treated differently by printers (and terminals). Others have been known to chop off the first character of all files sent to the system printer so that special utilities are needed to print ordinary text.\
To be on the safe side you should always provide an explicit carriage-control character at the start of each format specification and after each slash. Special care is needed in formats which use forced reversion. Normal single spacing is obtained with a blank, conveniently produced by the 
\f1 1X
\f0  edit descriptor. If you forget and accidentally print a number at the start of each record with a leading digit 
\f1 1
\f0  then each record will start a new page.\
The effect of 
\f1 +
\f0  as a carriage-control character would be more useful if its effects were more predictable. Some devices over-print the previous record, allowing the formation of composite characters (for example overprinting equals with a slash could give you a not-equals sign), while others append to it, and some (including many visual display terminals) erase what was there before. Obviously you cannot rely on this and in portable software there is no alternative but to ignore the 
\f1 +
\f0  case altogether.\
Standard Fortran can only use the four carriage-control characters listed in the table but many systems use other symbols for special formatting purposes, such as setting vertical spacing, changing fonts, and so on. One extension which is widely available is the use of the currency symbol 
\f1 $
\f0  to suppress carriage-return at the end of the line. This can be useful when producing terminal prompts as it allows the reply to be entered on the same line. There is, unfortunately, no way of doing this in Standard Fortran.\
The rules for list-directed output ensure that the lines are single-spaced by requiring at least one blank at the start of every record.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 10.12\'a0\'a0Input/Output Statements and Keywords\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The I/O statements fall into three groups:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls27\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}The data transfer statements 
\f1 READ
\f0  and 
\f1 WRITE
\f0 .\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}The file connection statements 
\f1 OPEN, CLOSE,
\f0  and 
\f1 INQUIRE
\f0 .\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}The file positioning statements 
\f1 REWIND
\f0  and 
\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 All these statements have a similar general form (except that only the 
\f1 READ
\f0  and 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statements can have a data-transfer list):
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 READ(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f0  
\i input-list
\f2\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 WRITE(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f0  
\i output-list
\f2\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 The items in each list are separated by commas. Those in the control list are usually specified by keywords, in which case the order does not matter, although it is conventional to have the unit identifier first. For compatibility with Fortran66, if the unit identifier does come first then the keyword 
\f1 UNIT=
\f0  may be omitted. Furthermore, when this keyword is omitted in 
\f1 READ
\f0  and 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statements and the format identifier is second its keyword may also be omitted. Thus these two statements are exactly equivalent:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       READ(UNIT=1, FMT=*, ERR=999) AMPS, VOLTS, HERTZ \
      READ(1, *, ERR=999) AMPS, VOLTS, HERTZ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Use of this abbreviated form is a matter of taste: for the sake of clarity the keywords will all be shown in other examples.\
Many of the keywords in the control-list can take a character expression as an argument: in such cases any trailing blanks in the value will be ignored. This makes it easy to use character variables to specify file names and characteristics.\
There is one general restriction on expressions used in all I/O statements: they must not call external functions which themselves execute further I/O statements. This restriction avoids the possibility of recursive calls to the I/O system.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 10.13\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 OPEN
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement is used to connect a file to an I/O unit and describe its characteristics. It can open an existing file or create a new one. If the unit is already connected to another file then this is closed before the new connection is made, so that it is impossible to connect two files simultaneously to the same unit. It is an error to try to connect more than one unit simultaneously to the same file. In the special case in which the unit and file are already connected to each other, the 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement may be used to alter the properties of the connection, although in practice only the 
\f1 BLANK=
\f0  (and sometimes 
\f1 RECL=
\f0 ) values can be changed in this way.\
The Fortran Standard does not specify the file position when an existing sequential file is opened. Although most operating systems behave sensibly, in portable software a 
\f1 REWIND
\f0  statement should be used to ensure that the file is rewound before you read it.\
The general form of the 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement is just:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 OPEN(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 The 
\i control-list
\i0  can contain any of the following items in any order:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 UNIT=
\f0\i integer-expression
\i0  species the I/O unit number which must be zero or above; the upper limit is system-dependent, typically 99 or 255. The unit identifier must always be given, there is no default value.\

\f1 STATUS=
\f0\i character-expression
\i0  describes or specifies the file status. The value must be one of:\

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth2000\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth9020\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'OLD'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 The file must exist.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth2000\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth9020\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'NEW'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 The file must not already exist, a new file is created.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth2000\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth9020\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'SCRATCH'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 An unnamed temporary file is created; it is deleted automatically when the program exits.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth2000\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth9020\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'UNKNOWN'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 The effect is system-dependent, but usually means that an old file will be used if one exists, otherwise a new file will be created.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 The default value is 
\f1 'UNKNOWN',
\f0  but it is unwise to omit the 
\f1 STATUS
\f0  keyword because the effect of 
\f1 'UNKNOWN'
\f0  is so ill-defined.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 FILE=
\f0\i character-expression
\i0  specifies the file-name (but any trailing blanks will be ignored). The forms of file-name acceptable are system-dependent: a complete file-specification on some operating systems may include the device, user-name, directory path, file-type, version number etc. and may require various punctuation marks to separate these. In portable software, where the name has to be acceptable to a variety of operating systems, short and simple names should be used. Alternatively the 
\f1 FILE=
\f0  identifier may be a character variable (or array element) so that the user can choose a file-name at run-time. There is no default for the file-name so one should be specified in all cases unless 
\f1 STATUS='SCRATCH'
\f0  in which case the file must not be named.\

\f1 ACCESS=
\f0\i character-expression
\i0  specifies the file access method. The value may be either:\

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth2400\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth8620\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'SEQUENTIAL'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 a sequential file: this is the default.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth2400\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth8620\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'DIRECT'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 a direct-access file: in this case the 
\f1 RECL=
\f0  keyword is also needed.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 FORM=
\f0\i character-expression
\i0  specifies the record format. The value may be either:\

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1820\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth3620\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'FORMATTED'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 the default for a sequential file.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1820\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth3620\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'UNFORMATTED'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 the default for a direct-access file.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 RECL=
\f0\i integer-expression
\i0  specifies the record length. This must be given for a direct-access file but not otherwise. The record-length is measured in characters for a formatted file, but is in system-dependent units (often numeric storage units) for an unformatted file.\

\f1 BLANK=
\f0\i character-expression
\i0  specifies how embedded and trailing blanks in numerical input fields of formatted files are to be treated (in the absence of explicit format descriptors 
\f1 BN
\f0  or 
\f1 BZ
\f0 ). The value may be either:\

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth840\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth5100\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'NULL'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 blanks treated as nulls, i.e.\'a0ignored: the default.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth840\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth5100\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 'ZERO'
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 blanks treated as zeros.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 The default value is likely to be the sensible choice in all cases.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 IOSTAT=
\f0\i integer-variable
\i0  (or array element) returns the I/O status code after execution of the 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement. This will be zero if no error has occurred, otherwise it will return a system-dependent positive value.\

\f1 ERR=
\f0\i label
\i0  transfers control to the labelled executable statement in the same program unit in the event of an error.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 10.14\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 CLOSE
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 CLOSE
\f0  statement is used to close a file and break its connection to a unit. The unit and the file (if it still exists) are then free for re-use in any way. If the specified unit is not connected to a file the statement has no effect. The general form of the statement is:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 CLOSE(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 where the 
\i control-list
\i0  may contain the following items:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 UNIT=
\f0\i integer-expression
\i0  specifies the unit number to close (the same as in the 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement).\

\f1 STATUS=
\f0\i character-expression
\i0  specifies the status of the file after closure. The expression must have a value of either: 
\f1 'KEEP' 
\f0 for the file to be preserved, or 
\f1 'DELETE'
\f0  for the file to be deleted after closure. The default is 
\f1 STATUS='KEEP'
\f0  except for files opened with 
\f1 STATUS='SCRATCH':
\f0  such files are always deleted after closure and 
\f1 STATUS='KEEP'
\f0  is not permitted.\

\f1 IOSTAT
\f0 teger-variable and 
\f1 ERR
\f0 label are both permitted, as in the 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement (but not much can go wrong with a 
\f1 CLOSE
\f0  statement).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 10.15\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 INQUIRE
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 INQUIRE
\f0  statement can be used in two slightly different forms: 
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 INQUIRE(UNIT=
\f0  
\i integer-expression, inquire-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 INQUIRE(FILE=
\f0  
\i character-expression, inquire-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 The first form, an inquire by unit, returns information about the unit and, if it is connected to a file, about the file as well. If it is not connected to a file then most of the arguments will be undefined or return a value of 
\f1 'UNKNOWN'
\f0  as appropriate.\
The second form, inquire by file, can always be used to find out whether a named file exists, i.e.\'a0can be opened by a Fortran program. Any trailing blanks in the character expression are ignored, and the forms of file-name acceptable are, as in the 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement, system-dependent. If the file exists and is connected to a unit then much more information can be obtained.\
The inquire-list may contain any of the items below. Note that all of them (except for 
\f1 ERR=label
\f0 ) return information by assigning a value to a named variable (or array element). The normal rules of assignment statements apply, so that character items may have any reasonable length and will return a value which is padded out with blanks to its declared length if necessary.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 IOSTAT=
\f0\i integer-variable
\i0  and 
\f1 ERR=
\f0\i label
\i0  can both be used in the same way as in 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  or 
\f1 CLOSE
\f0 ; note that they detect errors during the execution of the 
\f1 INQUIRE
\f0  statement itself, and do not reflect the state of the file or unit which is the subject of the inquiry.\

\f1 EXIST=
\f0\i logical-variable
\i0  sets the variable (or array-element) to 
\f1 .TRUE.
\f0  if the specified unit or file exists, or 
\f1 .FALSE.
\f0  if it does not. A unit exists if it has a number in the permitted range. A file exists if it can be used in an 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement. A file may appear not to exist merely because the operating system prevents its use, for example because a password is needed or because some other user has already opened it.\

\f1 OPENED=
\f0\i logical-variable
\i0  sets the variable to 
\f1 .TRUE.
\f0  if the specified unit (or file) is currently connected to a file (or unit) in the program.\

\f1 NUMBER=
\f0\i integer-variable
\i0  returns the unit number of a file which is connected to the variable; otherwise it becomes undefined.\

\f1 NAME=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns the file-name to the variable if the file has a name; if not it becomes undefined. In the case of an inquire by file the name may not be the same as that specified using 
\f1 FILE=
\f0  (because a device-name or directory path may have been added) but the name returned will always be suitable for use in an 
\f1 OPEN
\f0  statement.\

\f1 NAMED=
\f0\i logical-variable
\i0  sets the variable to 
\f1 .TRUE.
\f0  if the specified file has a name.\

\f1 ACCESS=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns the record access-method, either 
\f1 'SEQUENTIAL'
\f0  or 
\f1 'DIRECT'
\f0  if the file is connected; if it is not connected the variable becomes undefined.\

\f1 SEQUENTIAL=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns 
\f1 'YES'
\f0  if the file can be opened for sequential access, 
\f1 'NO'
\f0  if it cannot, and 
\f1 'UNKNOWN'
\f0  otherwise.\

\f1 DIRECT=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns 
\f1 'YES'
\f0  if the file can be opened for direct access, 
\f1 'NO'
\f0  if it cannot, and 
\f1 'UNKNOWN'
\f0  otherwise.\

\f1 FORM=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns 
\f1 'FORMATTED'
\f0  if the file is connected for formatted access, returns 
\f1 'UNFORMATTED'
\f0  if it is connected for unformatted access, or becomes undefined if there is no connection.\

\f1 FORMATTED=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns 
\f1 'YES'
\f0  if formatted access is permitted, 
\f1 'NO'
\f0  if it is not, or 
\f1 'UNKNOWN'
\f0  otherwise.\

\f1 UNFORMATTED=
\f0 character-variable returns 
\f1 'YES'
\f0  if unformatted access is permitted, 
\f1 'NO'
\f0  if it is not, or 
\f1 'UNKNOWN'
\f0  otherwise.\

\f1 RECL=
\f0\i integer-variable
\i0  returns the record length if the file is connected for direct-access but becomes undefined otherwise. Note that the units are characters for formatted files, but are system-dependent for unformatted files.\

\f1 NEXTREC=
\f0\i integer-variable
\i0  returns a number which is one higher than the last record read or written if the file is connected for direct access. If it is connected for direct access but no records have been transferred, the variable returns one. If the file is not connected for direct access the variable becomes undefined.\

\f1 BLANK=
\f0\i character-variable
\i0  returns 
\f1 'NULL'
\f0  or 
\f1 'BLANK'
\f0  if the file is connected for formatted access according to the way embedded and trailing blanks are to be treated. In other cases it becomes undefined.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 10.16\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 READ
\f0\b  and 
\f1\b0 WRITE
\f0\b  Statements\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 READ
\f0  statement reads information from one or more records on a file into a list of variables, array elements, etc. The 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement writes information from a list of items which may include variables, arrays, and expressions and produces one or more records on a file. Each 
\f1 READ
\f0  or 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement can only transfer one record on an unformatted file but on formatted files, including internal files, more than one record may be transferred, depending on the contents of the format specification.\
The two statements have the same general form:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 READ(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f0  
\i data-list
\f2\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 WRITE(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f0  
\i data-list
\f2\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 The 
\i control-list
\i0  must contain a unit identifier; the other items may be optional depending on the type of file. The 
\i data-list
\i0  is also optional: if it is absent the statement transfers one record (or possibly more under the control of a format specification).\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Unit Identifier\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 This may have any of the following forms:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 UNIT=
\f0  
\i integer-expression
\i0  The value of the expression must be zero or greater and must refer to a valid I/O unit.\
\

\f1 UNIT=*
\f0  For the standard pre-connected input or output file.\
\

\f1 UNIT=
\f0\i internal-file
\i0  The internal-file may be a variable, array-element, substring, or array of type character, see section 10.3.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Note that the keyword 
\f1 UNIT=
\f0  is optional if the unit identifier is the first item in the control list.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Format Identifier\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 A format identifier must be provided when using a formatted (or internal) file but not otherwise. It may have any of the following forms:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 FMT=
\f0\i label
\i0  The label of a 
\f1 FORMAT
\f0  statement in the same program unit.\
\

\f1 FMT=
\f0\i format
\i0  The format may be a character expression or character array containing a complete format specification (section 10.6).\
\

\f1 FMT=*
\f0  For list-directed formatting (section 10.10).\
Note that the keyword 
\f1 FMT=
\f0  is also optional if the format identifier is the second item in the control list and the first item is a unit identifier specified without its keyword.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Record Number\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 A record number identifier must be provided for direct-access files but not otherwise. It has the form:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 REC=
\f0 integer-expression\
The record number must be greater than zero; for 
\f1 READ
\f0  it must refer to a record which exists.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Error and End-of-file Identifiers\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 These may be provided in any combination, but 
\f1 END=
\f0 label is only valid when reading a sequential or internal file. See 10.5 for more information.
\f1 \
END=label \
ERR=label \
IOSTAT=integer-variable \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The data list of a 
\f1 READ
\f0  statement may contain variables, array-elements, character-substrings, or complete arrays of any data type. An array-name without subscripts represents all the elements of the array; this is not permitted for assumed-size dummy arguments in procedures (because the array size is indeterminate). The list may also contain implied 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loops (explained below).\
The data list of a 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement may contain any of the items permitted in a 
\f1 READ
\f0  statement and in addition expressions of any data type. As in all I/O statements, expressions must not themselves involve the execution of other I/O statements.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Implied 
\f1\b0 DO
\f0\b -loops\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The simplest and most efficient way to read or write all the elements of an array is to put its name, unsubscripted, in the data-transfer list. In the case of a multi-dimensional array the elements will be transferred in the normal storage sequence, with the first subscript varying most rapidly.\
An implied-DO loop allows the elements to be transferred selectively or in some non-standard order. The rules for an implied-DO are similar to that of an ordinary 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loop but the loop forms a single item in the data-transfer list and is enclosed by a pair of parentheses rather than by 
\f1 DO
\f0  and 
\f1 CONTINUE
\f0  statements. For example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       READ(UNIT=*, FMT=*) (ARRAY(I), I= IMIN, IMAX) \
      WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT=15) (M, X(M), Y(M), M=1,101,5) \
15    FORMAT(1X, I6, 2F12.3) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 A multi-dimensional array can be printed out in a transposed form. The next example outputs an array X(100,5) but with 5 elements across and 100 lines vertically:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       WRITE(UNIT=*, FMT=5) (I,I=1,5), \
     $                     ((L,X(L,I),I=1,5),L=1,100) \
5     FORMAT(1X,'LINE', 5I10, 100(/,1X,I4, 5F10.2)) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The first loop writes headings for the five columns, then the double loop writes a line-number for each line followed by five array elements. Note that the parentheses have to be matched and that a comma is needed after the inner right-parenthesis since the inner loop is just an item in the list contained in the outer loop.\
The implied 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loop has the general form:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 (
\f0  
\i data-list,
\i0  
\i loop-variable
\i0  = 
\i start,
\i0  
\i limit,
\i0  
\i step
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 where the rules for the 
\i start,
\i0  
\i limit,
\i0  and 
\i step
\i0  values are exactly as in an ordinary 
\f1 DO
\f0  statement. The 
\i loop-variable
\i0  (normally an integer) may be used within the data-list and this list may, in turn, include further complete implied-DO lists.\
If an error or end-of-file condition occurs in an implied 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loop then the loop-control variable will be undefined on exit; this means that an explicit 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loop is required to read an indefinite list of data records and exit with knowledge of how many items were actually input.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 10.17\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 REWIND
\f0\b  and 
\f1\b0 BACKSPACE
\f0\b  Statements\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 These file-positioning statements may only be used on external sequential files; most systems will restrict them to files stored on suitable peripheral devices such as discs or tapes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 REWIND
\f0  repositions a file to the beginning of information so that the next 
\f1 READ
\f0  statement will read the first record; if a 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement is used after 
\f1 REWIND
\f0  all existing records on the file are destroyed. 
\f1 REWIND
\f0  has no effect if the file is already rewound. If a 
\f1 REWIND
\f0  statement is used on a unit which is connected but does not exist (e.g.\'a0a pre-connected output file) it creates the file.\

\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0  moves the file position back by one record so that the record can be re-read or over-written. There is no effect if the file is already positioned at the beginning of information but it is an error to back-space a file which does not exist. It is also illegal to back-space over records written by list-directed formatting (because the number of records produced each time is system-dependent). A few operating systems find it difficult to implement the 
\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0  statement directly and actually manage it only by rewinding the file and spacing forward to the appropriate record. It is sometimes possible to avoid backspacing a file by allocating buffers within the program and, for a formatted file, using the internal file 
\f1 READ
\f0  and 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statements.\
These statements have similar general forms:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 REWIND(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 BACKSPACE(
\f0  
\i control-list
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 where the 
\i control-list
\i0  may contain:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0           UNIT=integer-expression \
          IOSTAT=integer-variable \
          ERR=label \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The unit identifier is compulsory, the others optional. If only the unit identifier is used then (for compatibility with Fortran66) an abbreviated form of the statement is permitted:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 REWIND
\f0  
\i integer-expression
\i0 \

\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0  
\i integer-expression
\i0 \
where the integer expression identifies the unit number.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs42 \cf0 11\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 DATA
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement is used to specify initial values for variables and array elements. The 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement is non-executable, but in a main program unit it has the same effect as a set of assignment statements at the very beginning of the program. Thus in a main program a 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement like this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        DATA LINES/625/, FREQ/50.0/, NAME/'PAL'/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 could replace several assignment statements:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        LINES = 625 \
       FREQ  = 50.0 \
       NAME  = 'PAL' \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This is more convenient, especially when initialising arrays, and efficient, since the work is done when the program is loaded.\
In a procedure, however, these two methods are not equivalent, especially in the case of items which are modified as the procedure executes. A 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement only sets the values once at the start of execution, whereas assignment statements will do so every time the procedure is called.\
It is important to distinguish between the 
\f1 DATA
\f0  and 
\f1 PARAMETER
\f0  statements. The 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement merely specifies an initial value for a variable (or array) which may be altered during the course of execution. The 
\f1 PARAMETER
\f0  statement specifies values for constants which cannot be changed without recompiling the program. If, however, you need an array of constants, for which there is no direct support in Fortran, you should use an ordinary array with a 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement to initialise its elements (and take care not to corrupt the contents afterwards).\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 11.1\'a0\'a0Defined and Undefined Values\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The value of each variable and array element is undefined at the start of execution unless it has been initialised with a DATA statement. An undefined value may only be used in executable statements in ways which cause it to become defined. An item can become defined by its use in any of the following ways:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls28\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}on the left-hand side of an assignment statement,\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}as the control variable of a 
\f1 DO
\f0  statement,\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}in the input list of a 
\f1 READ
\f0  statement,\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}as the internal file identifier of a 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement,\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}as the I/O status identifier in an I/O statement,\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}in an 
\f1 INQUIRE
\f0  statement except as file or unit number,\
{\listtext	\'95	}\
{\listtext	\'95	}in a procedure call provided that the corresponding dummy argument is defined before the procedure returns control.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 An undefined variable must not be used in any other way. Errors caused by the inadvertent use of undefined values are easy to make and sometimes have very obscure effects. It is important, therefore, to identify every item which needs to be initialised and provide a suitable set of 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements.\
Modern operating systems often clear the area of memory into which they load a program to prevent unauthorized access to the data used in the preceding job. A few operating systems preset their memory to a bit-pattern which corresponds to an illegal numerical value: this is a very helpful diagnostic facility since whenever an undefined variable is used in an expression it generates an error at run time. Other systems merely set their memory to zero: this makes it more difficult to track down the use of indefined variables and they may only come to light when a program is transported to another system. To rely on undefined variables and arrays having an initial value of zero is to leave the program completely at the mercy of changes to the operating system.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 11.2\'a0\'a0Initialising Variables\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The simplest form of the 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement consists of a list of the variable names each followed by a constant enclosed in a pair of slashes:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        DOUBLE PRECISION EPOCH \
       LOGICAL OPENED \
       CHARACTER INFILE*20 \
       DATA EPOCH/1950.0D0/, OPENED/.TRUE./, INFILE/'B:OBS.DAT'/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Note that 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements must follow all specification statements. An alternative form of the statement is to give first a complete list of names and then a separate list of constants:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       DATA EPOCH, OPENED, INFILE / 1950.0D0, .TRUE., 'B:OBS.DAT'/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 When there are many items to be initialised it is a matter of taste whether to use several 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements or to use one with many continuation lines. It is, of course, illegal to have the same name appearing twice.\
Character variables can be initialised in sections using the substring notation if this is more convenient:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       CHARACTER*52 LETTER \
      DATA LETTER(1:26)/'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ'/, \
     $     LETTER(27:) /'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz'/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 If the length of the character constant differs from that of the variable then the string is truncated or padded with blanks as in an assignment statement. The type conversion rules of assignment statements also apply to arithmetic items in 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 11.3\'a0\'a0Initialising Arrays\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 There are several ways of using 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements to initialise arrays, all of them simpler and more efficient than the equivalent set of 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loops. Perhaps the most common requirement is to initialise all the elements of an array: in this case the array name can appear without subscripts. If several of the elements are to have the same initial value a repeat count can precede any constant:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        REAL FLUX(1000) \
       DATA FLUX / 512*0.0, 488*-1.0 / \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The total number of constants must equal the number of array elements. The constants correspond to the elements in the array in the normal storage sequence, that is with the first subscript varying most rapidly.\
Named constants are permitted, but not constant expressions. The repeat count may be a literal or named integer constant. To initialise a multi-dimensional array with parameterised array bounds it is necessary to define another integer constant to hold the total number of elements:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        PARAMETER (NX = 800, NY = 360, NTOTAL = NX * NY) \
       DOUBLE PRECISION SCREEN(NX,NY), ZERO \
       PARAMETER (ZERO = 0.0D0) \
       DATA SCREEN / NTOTAL * ZERO / \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 If only a few array elements are to be initialised they can be listed individually:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        REAL SPARSE(50,50) \
       DATA SPARSE(1,1), SPARSE(50,50) / 1.0, 99.99999 / \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The third, and most complicated, option is to use an implied-DO loop. This operates in much the same way as an implied-DO in an I/O statement:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        INTEGER ODD(10) \
       DATA (ODD(I),I=1,10,2)/ 5 * 43/ \
       DATA (ODD(I),I=2,10,2)/ 5 * 0 / \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This example has initialised all the odd numbered elements to one value and all the even numbered elements to another. Note that the loop control variable (I in this example) has a scope which does not extend outside the section of the 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement in which it is used. Any integer variable may be used as a loop control index in a 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement without effects elsewhere; the value of I itself is not defined by these statements.\
When initialising part of a multi-dimensional array it may occasionally be useful to nest 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loops like this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        DOUBLE PRECISION FIELD(5,5) \
       DATA ((FIELD(I,J),I=1,J), J=1,5) / 15 * -1.0D0 / \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This specifies initial values only for the upper triangle of the square array FIELD.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 11.4\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 DATA
\f0\b  Statements in Procedures\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 In procedures, 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements perform a role for which assignment statements are no substitute. It is quite often necessary to arrange for some action to be carried out at the start of the first call but not subsequently, such as opening a file or initialising a variable or array which accumulates information during subsequent calls.\
If information is preserved in a local variable or array from one invocation to another a 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statement (described in section 9.11) is also needed. Indeed, in general any object initialised in a 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement in a procedure also needs to be named in a 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statement unless its value is never altered.\
In the next example the procedure opens a data file on its first call, using a logical variable OPENED to remember the state of the file.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        SUBROUTINE LOOKUP(INDEX, RECORD)  \
       INTEGER INDEX \
       REAL  RECORD \
       LOGICAL OPENED  \
       SAVE OPENED \
       DATA OPENED / .FALSE. /  \
*On first call OPENED is false so open the file. \
       IF(.NOT. OPENED) THEN \
            OPEN(UNIT=57, FILE='HIDDEN.DAT', STATUS='OLD', \
     $            ACCESS='DIRECT', RECL=100) \
            OPENED = .TRUE. \
       END IF \
       READ(UNIT=57, REC=INDEX) RECORD \
       END \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Here, for simplicity, the I/O unit number is a literal constant. The procedure would be more modular if the unit number were also an argument of the procedure or if it contained some code, using the 
\f1 INQUIRE
\f0  statement, to determine for itself a suitable unused unit number.\
There is, of course, no corresponding way to determine which is the last call to the procedure so that the file can be closed, but this is not strictly necessary as the Fortran system closes all files automatically when the program exits.\
Note that 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements cannot be used to initialise variables or arrays which are dummy arguments of a procedure, nor the variable which has the same name as the function.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 11.5\'a0\'a0General Rules\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The general form of the 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement is:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 DATA
\f0  
\i nlist
\i0  
\f1 /
\f0  
\i clist
\i0  
\f1 /,
\f0  
\i nlist
\i0  
\f1 /
\f0  
\i clist
\i0  
\f1 /,
\f0  ...
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 Where 
\i nlist
\i0  is a list of variable names, array names, substring names, and implied-DO lists, and 
\i clist
\i0  is a list of items which may be literal or named constants or either of these preceded by a repeat-count and an asterisk. The repeat-count can also be an unsigned integer constant or named constant.\
The comma which precedes each list of names except the first is optional. An implied-DO list has the general form:
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 (
\f0  
\i dlist,
\i0  
\i intvar
\i0  
\i start,
\i0  
\i limit,
\i0  
\i step
\i0  
\f1 )
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0 Where 
\i dlist
\i0  is a list of implied-DO lists and array elements; 
\i intvar
\i0  is an integer variable called the loop-control variable; 
\i start
\i0 , 
\i limit
\i0 , and 
\i step
\i0  are integer expressions in which all the operands must be integer constants or loop-control variables of outer implied-DO lists.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 DATA
\f0  statements cannot be used to initialise items in the blank common block; items in named common blocks can only be initialised within a 
\f1 BLOCK DATA
\f0  program unit (see section 12.4).\
The 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements in each program unit must follow all specification statements but they can be interspersed with executable statements and statement function statements. It is, however, best to follow the usual practice of putting all DATA statements before any of the executable statements.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs42 \cf0 12\'a0\'a0Common Blocks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 A common block is a list of variables and arrays stored in a named area which may be accessed directly in more than one program unit. Common blocks are mainly used to transfer information from one program unit to another; they can be used in as an alternative to argument-list transfers or in addition to them.\
Common blocks are sometimes used to fit large programs into small computers by arranging for several program units to share a common pool of memory. This is not a recommended programming practice and is likely to become redundant with the spread of virtual-memory operating systems.\
The name of a common block is an external name which must be different from all other global names, such as those of procedures, in the executable program. The variables and arrays stored with the block cannot be initialised in the normal way, but only in a 
\f1 BLOCK DATA
\f0  program unit which was invented especially for this purpose.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 12.1\'a0\'a0Using Common Blocks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 In most cases the best way to pass information from one program unit to another is to use the procedure argument list mechanism. This preserves the modularity and independence of procedures as much as possible. Argument lists are, however, less satisfactory in a group of procedures forming a package which have to share a large amount of information with each other. Procedure argument lists then tend to become long, cumbersome, and even inefficient. If this package of procedures is intended for general use it is quite important to keep the external interface as uncomplicated as possible. This can be achieved by using the procedure argument lists only for import of information from and export to the rest of the program, and handling the communications between one procedure in the package and another with common blocks. The user is then free to ignore the internal workings of the package.\
For example, in a simple package to handle a pen-plotter you may want to provide simple procedure calls such as:\

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1960\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth4940\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 CALL PLOPEN
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Initialise the plotting device\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1960\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth4940\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 CALL SCALE(F)
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Set the scaling factor to F.\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1960\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth4940\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 CALL MOVE(X,Y)
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Move the pen to position (X,Y)\cell \row

\itap1\trowd \taflags0 \trgaph108\trleft-108 \trbrdrl\brdrnil \trbrdrt\brdrnil \trbrdrr\brdrnil 
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth1960\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx4320
\clvertalc \clshdrawnil \clwWidth4940\clftsWidth3 \clmart10 \clmarl10 \clmarb10 \clmarr10 \clbrdrt\brdrnil \clbrdrl\brdrnil \clbrdrb\brdrnil \clbrdrr\brdrnil \clpadt20 \clpadl20 \clpadb20 \clpadr20 \gaph\cellx8640
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 CALL DRAW(X,Y)
\f0 \cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Draw a line from the last pen position to (X,Y).\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 These procedures clearly have to pass information from one to another about the current pen position, scaling factor, etc. A suitable common block definition might look like this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /PLOT/ OPENED, ORIGIN(2), PSCALE, NUMPEN \
       LOGICAL OPENED \
       INTEGER NUMPEN \
       REAL PSCALE, ORIGIN \
       SAVE /PLOT/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 These specification statements would be needed in each procedure in the package.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Common Block Names\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 A program unit can access the contents of any common block by quoting its name in a 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statement. Common block names are always enclosed in a pair of slashes and can only be used in 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  and 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statements. The common block itself has no data type and has a global name which must be distinct from the names of all program units. The name should also be distinct from all local names in each program units which access the block. Each program unit can make use of any number of different common blocks. There is also a special blank or un-named common block with unique properties which are covered in section 12.2 below.\
The variables and arrays within a common block do not have any global status: they are associated with items in blocks bearing the same name in other program units only by their position within the block. Thus, if in one program unit specifies:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /OBTUSE/ X(3) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 and in another:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /OBTUSE/ A, B, C \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 then, assuming the data types are the same, X(1) corresponds to A, X(2) to B, and X(3) to C. The 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statements here are effectively setting up different names or aliases for the same set of memory locations. The data types do not have to match provided the overall length is the same, but it is generally only possible to transfer information from one program unit to another if the corresponding items have the same data type. If they do not, when one item becomes defined all names for the same location which have a different data type become undefined. There is one minor exception to this rule: information may be transferred from a complex variable (or array element) to two variables of type real (or vice-versa) since these are directly associated with its real and imaginary parts.\
Usually it is necessary to arrange for corresponding items to have identical data types; it also minimises confusion if the same symbolic names are used as well. The simplest way to achieve this is to use an 
\f1 INCLUDE
\f0  statement, if your system provides one. The include-file should contain not only the 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statement but also all the associated type and 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statements which are necessary. It is, of course, still necessary to recompile every program unit which accesses the common block whenever its definition is altered significantly.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Declaring Arrays\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The bounds of an array can be declared in the 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statement itself, or in a separate 
\i type
\i0  or
\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 DIMENSION
\f0  statement, but only in one of them. Thus:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /DEMO/ ARRAY(5000) \
       DOUBLE PRECISION ARRAY \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 is exactly equivalent to:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /DEMO/ ARRAY \
       DOUBLE PRECISION ARRAY(5000) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 or even:
\f1 \
       COMMON /DEMO/ ARRAY \
       DOUBLE PRECISION ARRAY \
       DIMENSION ARRAY(5000) \
\

\f0 but the verbosity of the third form has little to recommend it.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Data Types\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The normal data type rules apply to variables and arrays in each common block. A type statement is not required if the initial letter rule would have the required effect, but type statements are advisable, especially if the implied-type rules are anywhere affected by 
\f1 IMPLICIT
\f0  statements. Type statements may precede or follow the 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statement. Similarly the lengths of character items should be specified in a separate type statement: these cannot be specified in the 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statement.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Storage Units\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The length of each common block is measured in storage units, as described in section 5.1. In summary, integer, real, and logical items occupy one numeric storage unit each; complex and double precision items occupy two each. To maximise portability, character storage units are considered incommensurate with numerical storage units. For this reason character and non-character items cannot be mixed in the same common block.\
In practice this often means that two common blocks are needed to hold a particular data structure: one for the character items and one for all the others. If, in the first example, it had been necessary for the plotting package to store a plot title this would have to appear in a separate common block such as:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /PLOTC/ TITLE \
       CHARACTER TITLE*40 \
       SAVE /PLOTC/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 It is good practice to use related names for the blocks to indicate that the character and non-character items are used in conjunction.\
The length of a named common block must be the same in each program unit in which it appears. Obviously the easiest way to ensure this is to make the common block contents identical in each program unit. Note, however, that there is no requirement for data types to match, or for them to be listed in any particular order, provided the items are not used for information transfer, and provided the total length of the block is the same in each case. Thus these common blocks are both 2000 numerical storage units in length:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /SAME/ G(1000) \
       DOUBLE PRECISION G \
\
       COMMON /SAME/ A, B, C, R(1997) \
       REAL A, R \
       LOGICAL B \
       INTEGER C \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Items in a common block are stored in consecutive memory locations. Unfortunately there are a few computer systems which require double precision and complex items to be stored in even-numbered storage locations: these may find it hard to cope with blocks which contain a mixture of data types. Machines with this defect can nearly always be placated by arranging for all double precision and complex items to come at the beginning of each block.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 SAVE
\f0\b  Statements and Common Blocks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 Items in common blocks may become undefined when a procedure returns control to the calling unit just like local variables and arrays. This will not, however, occur in the case of the blank common block nor in any common block which is also declared in a program unit which is higher up the current chain of procedure calls. Since the main program unit is always at the top of the chain any common block declared in the main program can never become undefined in this way. In all other cases it is prudent to use 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statements.\
The individual items in common blocks cannot be specified in a 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statement, only the common block name itself. Thus:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        SAVE /SAME/, /DEMO/ \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 If a common block is saved in any program unit then it must be saved in all of them. The 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statement ought therefore to be included with the 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  and associated type statements if 
\f1 INCLUDE
\f0  statements are used. If the program is later modified so that the common block is also declared in the main program this will bring a 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statement into the main program unit, but although it then has no effect, it does no harm.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Restrictions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The dummy arguments of a procedure cannot be members of a common block nor, in a function, can the variable which has same name as the function. There are also some restrictions on the use of common block items as actual arguments of procedure calls because of the possibility of multiple definition. For example, if a procedure is defined like this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        SUBROUTINE SILLY(ARG) \
       COMMON /BLOCK/ COM \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 And the same common block is also used in the calling unit, with a common block item as the actual argument, such as:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        PROGRAM DUMMY \
       COMMON /BLOCK/ VALUE \
*... \
       CALL SILLY(VALUE) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 Then both ARG and COM within the subroutine SILLY are associated with the same item, VALUE, and it is therefore illegal to assign a new value to either of them.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 12.2\'a0\'a0Blank Common Blocks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Common blocks are sometimes also used to reduce the total amount of memory used by a program by arranging for several program units to share the same set of memory locations. This is a difficult and risky procedure which should not be attempted unless all else fails.\
Most Fortran systems operate a storage allocation system which is completely static: each program unit has a separate allocation of memory for its local variables and arrays. If several procedures each need to use large arrays internally the total amount of memory occupied by the program may be rather large. If a set of procedures can be identified which are invoked in sequence, rather than one calling another, it may be feasible to reduce the total memory allocation by arranging for them to share a storage area. Each will use the same common block for their internal array space.\
Named common blocks are required to have the same length in each program unit: if they are used it is necessary to work out which one needs the most storage and pad out all the others to same length. An alternative is to the use the special blank (or un-named) common block which has the useful property that it may have a different length in different program units.\
In one program unit, for example, you could specify:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON // DUMMY(10000) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 and in another\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMPLEX SERIES(512,512), SLICE(512), EXPECT(1024) \
       COMMON // SERIES, SLICE, EXPECT \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The blank common block has two other special properties. Firstly it cannot be initialised by a 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statement even within a 
\f1 BLOCK DATA
\f0  program unit (but this is not a serious limitation for a block used just for scratch storage). Secondly items within the blank common block never become undefined as a result of a procedure exit. For this reason the blank common block cannot be specified in a 
\f1 SAVE
\f0  statement.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 12.3\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 COMMON
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 A program unit may contain any number of 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statements, each of which can define contents for any number of different common blocks. 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  statements are specification statements and have a general form:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 COMMON /
\f0  name
\f1 /
\f0  list-of-items , 
\f1 /
\f0  name 
\f1 /
\f0  list-of-items ...\
Each name is defined as a common block name, which has global scope. The Fortran Standard allows it to use the same name as an intrinsic function, a local variable, or local array but not that of a named constant or an intrinsic function. Each list of items can contain names of variables and arrays. The array name may be followed by a dimension specification provided that each array is only dimensioned once in each program unit. The comma shown before the second and subsequent block-name is optional.\
The name of the blank common block is normally specified as two consecutive slashes (ignoring any intervening blanks) but if it is the first block in the statement then the pair of slashes may be omitted.\
The contents of a common block are a concatenation of the all the definitions for it in the program unit. Thus:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        COMMON /ONE/ A, B, C, /TWO/ ALPHA, BETA, GAMMA \
       COMMON /TWO/ DELTA \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 defines two blocks, /ONE/ contains three items while /TWO/ contains four of them.\
In procedures, variables which are dummy arguments or which are the same as the function name cannot appear in common blocks.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 12.4\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 BLOCK DATA
\f0\b  Program Units\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The block data program unit is a special form of program unit which is required only if it is necessary to specify initial values for variables and arrays in named common blocks. The program unit starts with a 
\f1 BLOCK DATA
\f0  statement, ends with an 
\f1 END
\f0  statement, and contains only specification and 
\f1 DATA
\f0  statements. Comment lines are also permitted. The block data program unit is not executable and it is not a procedure.\
The next example initialises the items in the common block for the plotting package used in section 12.1, so that the initial pen position is at the origin, the scaling factor starts at one, and so on. Thus a suitable program unit would be:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        BLOCK DATA SETPLT \
*SETPLT initialises the values used in the plotting package. \
       COMMON /PLOT/ OPENED, ORIGIN(2), PSCALE, NUMPEN \
       LOGICAL OPENED \
       INTEGER NUMPEN \
       REAL PSCALE, ORIGIN \
       SAVE /PLOT/ \
       DATA OPENED/.FALSE./, ORIGIN/2*0.0/, PSCALE/1.0/ \
       DATA NUMPEN/-1/ \
       END \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 A block data unit can specify initial values for any number of named common blocks (blank common cannot be initialised). Each common block must be complete but it is not necessary to specify initial values for all of the items within it. There can be more than one block data program unit, but a given common block cannot appear in more than one of them.\
For compatibility with Fortran66 it is also possible to have one un-named block data program unit in a program.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 Linking Block Data Program Units\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 If, when linking a program, one of the modules containing a procedure is accidentally omitted the linker is almost certain to produce an error message. But, unless additional precautions are taken, this will not occur if a block data subprogram unit is omitted. The program may even appear to work without it, but is likely to produce the wrong answer.\
There is a simple way to guard against this possibility: the name of the block data unit should be specified in an 
\f1 EXTERNAL
\f0  statement in at least some of the program units in which the common block is used. There is no harm in declaring it in all of them. This ensures that a link-time reference will be generated if any of these other program units are used. There is a slight snag to this technique if an 
\f1 INCLUDE
\f0  statement is used to bring the common block definition into each program unit including the block data unit. In order to avoid a self-reference, the include-file should not contain the 
\f1 EXTERNAL
\f0  statement.\
Despite this slight complication, this is a simple and valuable precaution. It also makes it possible to hold block data units on object libraries and retrieve them automatically when they are required, just like all other types of subprogram unit.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs42 \cf0 13\'a0\'a0Obsolete and Deprecated Features\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 None of the features covered here should be used in new software: some of them are completely obsolete, others have practical defects which make them unsuitable for use in well-structured software. These brief descriptions are provided only for the benefit of programmers who have to understand and update programs designed in earlier years.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.1\'a0\'a0Storage of Character Strings in Non-character Items\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Before the advent of the character data type it was possible to store text in arithmetic variables and arrays, although only very limited manipulation was possible. The number of characters which could be stored in each item was entirely system-dependent. One side-effect is that many systems still allow the A format descriptor to match input/output items of arithmetic types; this sometimes allows mismatches between data-transfer lists and format descriptors to pass undetected.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.2\'a0\'a0Arithmetic 
\f1\b0 IF
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 This is an executable statement with the form:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 IF(
\f0  arithmetic-expression 
\f1 )
\f0  label1, label2, label3\
It generally provides a three-way branch (but two of the labels may be identical for a two-way branch). The expression may be an integer, real, or double-precision value: control is transferred to the statement attached to label1 if its value is negative, label2 if zero, or label3, if positive.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.3\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 ASSIGN
\f0\b  and assigned 
\f1\b0 GO TO
\f0\b  Statements\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 These two executable statements are normally used together. The 
\f1 ASSIGN
\f0  statement assigns a statement label value to an integer variable. When this has been done the variable no longer has an arithmetic value. If the label is attached to an executable statement the variable can only be used in an assigned 
\f1 GO TO
\f0  statement; if attached to a 
\f1 FORMAT
\f0  statement the variable can only be used in a 
\f1 READ
\f0  or 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement. The general forms of these statements are:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 ASSIGN
\f0  label 
\f1 TO
\f0  integer-variable\

\f1 GO TO
\f0  integer-variable ,(label, label, ... label)\
In the assigned 
\f1 GO TO
\f0  statement the comma and the entire parenthesised list of labels is optional.\
Assigned 
\f1 GO TO
\f0  can be used to provide a linkage to and from a section of a program unit acting as an internal subroutine, but is not a very convenient or satisfactory way of doing this.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.4\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 PAUSE
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs30 \cf0 PAUSE
\f0  is an executable statement which halts the program in such a way that execution can be resumed in some way by the user (or on some systems by the computer operator). The general forms of the statement are identical to those of 
\f1 STOP,
\f0  for example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        PAUSE 'NOW MOUNT THE NEXT TAPE' \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 or
\f1 \
       PAUSE  54321 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 PAUSE
\f0  can be replaced by one 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  and one 
\f1 READ
\f0  statement: this is more flexible and less system-dependent.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.5\'a0\'a0Alternate 
\f1\b0 RETURN
\f0\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The alternate 
\f1 RETURN
\f0  mechanism can be used in subroutines (but not external functions) to arrange a transfer of control to some labelled statement on completion of a 
\f1 CALL
\f0  statement. In order to use it the arguments of the 
\f1 CALL
\f0  statement must include a list of labels, each preceded by an asterisk. These labels are attached to points in the calling program unit at which execution may resume after the 
\f1 CALL
\f0  statement is executed. For example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        CALL BAD(X, Y, Z, *150, *220, *390) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The corresponding subroutine statement will have asterisks as dummy arguments for each label specification:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        SUBROUTINE BAD(A, B, C, *, *, *) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The return point depends on the value of an integer expression given in the 
\f1 RETURN
\f0  statement. Thus:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        RETURN 2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 will cause execution to be resumed at the statement attached to the second label argument, 220 in this case. If the value of the integer expression in the 
\f1 RETURN
\f0  statement is not in the range 1 to n (where there are n label arguments) or a plain 
\f1 RETURN
\f0  statement is executed, then execution resumes at the statement after the 
\f1 CALL
\f0  in the usual way.\
The mechanism can be used for error-handling but is not very flexible as information cannot be passed through more than one procedure level. It is better to use an integer argument to return a status value and use that with an 
\f1 IF
\f0  (or even a computed 
\f1 GO TO
\f0  statement) in the calling program.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.6\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 ENTRY
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs30 \cf0 ENTRY
\f0  statements can be used to specify additional entry points in external functions and subroutines. 
\f1 ENTRY
\f0  is a non-executable statement which has the same form as a 
\f1 SUBROUTINE
\f0  statement. An 
\f1 ENTRY
\f0  statement may be used at any point in a procedure but all specification statements relating to its dummy arguments must appear in the appropriate place with the other specification statements. If the main entry point is a 
\f1 SUBROUTINE
\f0  statement then all alternative entry points can be called in the same way as subroutines; if it is a 
\f1 FUNCTION
\f0  statement than all alternative entry point names can be used as functions. If the main entry point is a character function then all the alternative entry points must also have that type. Alternative entry points may have different lists of dummy arguments; it is up to the user to ensure that all those returning information to the calling program are properly defined before exit.\
The rules for the 
\f1 ENTRY
\f0  statement are necessarily complicated so it is easy to make mistakes. It is generally better, or at least less unsatisfactory, to use a set of separate procedures which share information using common blocks.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.7\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 EQUIVALENCE
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs30 \cf0 EQUIVALENCE
\f0  is a specification statement which causes two or more items (variables or arrays) to be associated with each other, i.e.\'a0to correspond to the same area of memory. Character items can only be associated with other character items; otherwise the data types do not have to match. As with common blocks, however, transfer of information is only permitted via associated items if their data types match. A special exception is made for a complex item which is associated with two real ones.\

\f1 EQUIVALENCE
\f0  statements can be used fairly safely to provide a simple variable name as an alias for a particular array element or to associate a character variable with an array of the same length. For example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        CHARACTER STRING*80, ARRAY(80)*1 \
       EQUIVALENCE (STRING, ARRAY) \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 This slightly simplifies access to a single character in the string as the form ARRAY(K) can be used instead of STRING(K:K).\
The general form of the statement is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 EQUIVALENCE
\f0  ( v, v, ... v ), ( v, v, ... v ), ...\
where each v is a variable, array, array element, or substring. Dummy arguments of procedures (and variables which are external function names) cannot appear. An array name without subscripts refers to the first element of the array. It is illegal to associate two or more elements of the same array, directly or indirectly, or do anything which conflicts with the storage sequence rules. Variables and arrays in common blocks can appear in 
\f1 EQUIVALENCE
\f0  statements but this has the effect of bringing all the associated items into the block. They can be used to extend the contents of the block upwards, subject to the rules for common block length, but not downwards.\
Although the 
\f1 EQUIVALENCE
\f0  statement does have a few legitimate uses it is usually encountered in programs where the rules of Fortran are broken to obtain some special effect. Programs which do this are rarely portable.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.8\'a0\'a0Specific Names of Intrinsic Functions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

