\b\fs34 \cf0 13.9\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 PRINT
\f0\b  Statement and simplified 
\f1\b0 READ
\f0\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 PRINT
\f0  statement can produce formatted or list-directed output on the standard pre-connected output file. Thus these two statements have exactly the same effect:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        PRINT fmt, data-list \
       WRITE(*, fmt) data-list \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 The 
\f1 PRINT
\f0  statement is limited in its functionality and misleading, since there is no necessity for its output to appear in printed form.\
In a similar way there is a simplified form of READ statement, so these have the same effect:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        READ fmt, data-list \
       READ(*, fmt) data-list \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.10\'a0\'a0
\f1\b0 END FILE
\f0\b  Statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The 
\f1 END FILE
\f0  statement has the same general forms as 
\f1 REWIND
\f0  and 
\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0 :\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0        END FILE(UNIT=unit, ERR=label, IOSTAT=int-var) \
       END FILE unit \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 It appends a special ``end-file'' record to a sequential file which is designed to trigger the end-of-file detection mechanism on subsequent input. No further records can be written to the file after this end-file record, i.e.\'a0the next operation must be 
\f1 CLOSE
\f0 , 
\f1 REWIND,
\f0  or 
\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0 .\
The statement seems to be superfluous on almost all current systems since they can detect the end of an input file without its aid. The Fortran Standard requires that the end-file record be treated as a physical record, so that after an end-of-file condition has been detected an explicit 
\f1 BACKSPACE
\f0  operation is required before any new data records are appended. This notion is somewhat artificial and not all systems implement it correctly. This is one of the few cases where a deliberate departure from the Fortran Standard can enhance portability.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 13.11\'a0\'a0Obsolete Format Descriptors\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 The data descriptor 
\f1 Dw.d
\f0  is exactly equivalent to Ew.d on input; on output it is similar except that the exponent will use the letter 
\f1 D
\f0  instead of 
\f1 E
\f0 . Real and double precision data items can be read equally well by 
\f1 D,
\f0  
\f1 E,
\f0  
\f1 F,
\f0  or 
\f1 G
\f0  descriptors.\
The format descriptor 
\f1 nHstring 
\f0 is exactly equivalent to 
\f1 'string' 
\f0 (where n is an unsigned integer constant giving the length of the string). When used with a formatted 
\f1 WRITE
\f0  statement the string is copied to the output record. The 
\f1 nH
\f0  form does not require apostrophes to be doubled within the string but does require an accurate character count.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs42 \cf0 14\'a0\'a0Common Extensions to the Fortran Standard\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 Almost before the official Standard (ANSI X3.9-1978) for Fortran77 had been defined, various software producers started to add their own favourite features. The US Department of Defense issued in 1988 a supplement called MIL-STD-1753 setting out a list of extensions that it required Fortran systems to support if they were to tender for DoD contracts. This requirement later spread to other areas of Federal Government procurement, so these extensions are now almost universally provided and can be used with confidence without reducing portability.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\ql\qnatural

\b\fs34 \cf0 14.1\'a0\'a0MIL-STD-1753 Extensions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs30 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 IMPLICIT NONE
\f0\b  statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 This statement says that there are no default data types in this program unit, so that all named items (variables, arrays, constants, and external functions) must have their data type specified in an explicit 
\i type
\i0  statement. It must appear before all these specification statements and cannot be used together with any other 
\f1 IMPLICIT
\f0  statement in the same program unit. Although novice programmers find it tedious to have to declare each name before using it, the benefits are considerable in that mis-spelled names come to light much more easily, and most professional programmers find it a worth-while investment.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 INCLUDE
\f0\b  statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The 
\f1 INCLUDE
\f0  statement specifies the name of another file which contains some source code. It is most often used to contain a set of specification statements which are common to a number of different program units, for example 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  blocks and their associated 
\i type
\i0  statements, or a list of common constants such as 
\f2 p
\f0 . The form of file-name is, of course, system dependent. In portable software it is prudent to choose a simple name which is likely to be acceptable to most operating systems. For example:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0       INCLUDE 'trig.inc'\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0 \cf0 where the file 
\f1 trig.inc
\f0  (or maybe 
\f1 TRIG.INC
\f0 ) contains:
\f1 \
      REAL PI, TWOPI, RTOD\
      PARAMETER (PI = 3.14159265, TWOPI=2.0*PI, RTOD=PI/180.0)\
\

\f0 If such constants are defined only once, it is much easier to ensure that they are correct. Similarly the definition of a 
\f1 COMMON
\f0  block in only one place ensures that its consistency throughout the program.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 DO
\f0\b -loops with 
\f1\b0 END DO
\f0\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\b0 \cf0 The Fortran77 Standard seemed deficient in pairing 
\f1 IF
\f0  with 
\f1 END IF
\f0  but not 
\f1 DO
\f0  with 
\f1 END DO
\f0 . This extension is widely available and helpful in that it avoids the need to use a different statement label on each loop. For example:
\f1 \
      DO J = 1,NPTS\
         SUM   = SUM + X(I)\
         SUMSQ = SUMSQ + X(I)**2\
      END DO\
\

\f0 It is good practice to indent the lines between the 
\f1 DO
\f0  and 
\f1 END DO
\f0  statements to make the repeated section obvious. The appearance of a statement label in such code usually marks the destination of a 
\f1 GO TO
\f0  statement, and alerts the programmer to some unusual alteration to the standard sequence of operations. Where only labelled 
\f1 DO
\f0 -loops are used, such exceptions are harder to spot.\
